t a week later I received a letter the peculiar Russian of which can hardly be appreciated in translation.

“Esteemed Sir,” it read. “You have been pursuing me all my life. Good friends of mine, after reading your books, have turned away from me thinking that I was the author of those depraved, decadent writings. In 1941, and again in 1943, I was arrested in France by the Germans for things I never had said or thought. Now in America, not content with having caused me all sorts of troubles